column106: In this study, I formed my initial guesses by trying to recall any relevant facts or general knowledge I had about each topic. When I wasn‚Äôt sure of the exact answer, I tried to think about the plausible range of values and then chose a guess that represented the middle of what I thought was likely ‚Äî as the instructions recommended.
column107:
First, I considered whether I recognized the source. If it was a mainstream or well-established outlet (like Associated Press or Reuters), I assumed it had more rigorous editorial standards, making it more likely to be true. If the source was unfamiliar, had a sensationalist tone, or resembled outlets known for clickbait or conspiracy theories, I leaned toward it being less credible.

Second, I looked at the language and framing. If a headline or statement seemed overly emotional, biased, or exaggerated, I considered it more likely to be false or misleading. In contrast, neutral or fact-based language increased my confidence in the truthfulness.

Finally, I tried to think about whether the claim made sense with what I know about the world. If something felt implausible or contradicted well-known facts, I questioned its accuracy.

column106:
When making my initial guesses, I tried to rely on a combination of what I already knew or could reasonably estimate, along with general knowledge and logic. For example:
	‚Ä¢	For the U.S. population question, I thought about recent census data and typical population growth rates, which helped me estimate a number close to current official estimates.
	‚Ä¢	For questions related to happiness or subjective measures, I considered national averages and whether there might be any notable differences for specific groups, but I kept my guesses close to the average since I had no strong evidence otherwise.
	‚Ä¢	For geographic questions like the latitude of the U.S. center, I drew on what I remembered about U.S. geography and known locations.
	‚Ä¢	When I received news messages, I assessed their credibility based on how plausible the claim was compared to my initial guess and general knowledge.
	‚Ä¢	For questions involving beliefs about news trust, I considered human psychology‚Äîlike people‚Äôs tendency to trust information that aligns with their hopes or political views.

Overall, I tried to be honest and reasonable with each guess, balancing what I knew with uncertainty where appropriate.
column107:
When deciding whether a news source was more likely True News or False News, I focused mainly on how consistent the message was with what I knew or logically expected about the question. For example:
	‚Ä¢	If the news said the answer was greater or less than my guess, I checked whether that made sense given my initial estimate and general knowledge. If it contradicted obvious facts or seemed unlikely, I leaned toward it being False News.
	‚Ä¢	I also considered whether the news message fit with typical patterns or reasonable trends. For example, if my guess was already near a well-known benchmark (like the geographic center of the U.S.), I was skeptical of news claiming it was far off.
	‚Ä¢	Sometimes, the news message challenged my guess but still felt plausible, so I gave some chance it could be True News.
	‚Ä¢	I tried to avoid letting my personal biases overly influence my judgment and focused on the internal logic and consistency.
	‚Ä¢	Overall, I balanced skepticism with openness, giving a probability rating rather than a strict yes/no, to reflect uncertainty.

This approach helped me weigh the credibility of each news message based on how well it aligned with evidence and logic.

column106:
For Round 1, I knew that the official estimates of the population of the U.S. in early 2025 were roughly 333-334 million. So, I chose 333 million as a reasonable ‚Äúmedian‚Äù estimate that seemed to me to be most likely.
In Round 2, there is no data that suggested the general population of Sagittarians differed from the overall population for life-satisfaction. Since 45.5% of all adults were ‚Äúcompletely/very happy,‚Äù Astrological sign couldn‚Äôt make that much difference, and 45.5% is what I expected.
In Round 3, I recalled that the U.S. National Geodetic Survey puts it at approximately 39¬∞ 50‚Ä≤ N, and that would be roughly 39.83¬∞ N: So, I rounded off to 39.8.
column107:
For Round 1, since I estimated the actual population to be roughly 334 million, "less than 333" must be false. So, with extremely high confidence, I predicted the message to be from False News (picked 0/10 True, 10/10 False).
For Round 2, I was equally uncertain if the rate for Sagittarius is above or below 45.5 %. As my prior assumption lay in equal chances of a Sagittarius ‚Äúcompletely/very happy‚Äù rate being above or below 45.5 %, seeing ‚Äúbelow 45.5‚Äù is equally as likely to be a truth as a lie. My probability was thus still 50/50 (I marked 5/10 True, 5/10 False).
In Round 3, I knew the actual figure to be approximately 39.83. My choice was 10/10 True News, 0/10 False News.

column106:
Well, let's see. There's no real strategy when it comes to me. When it comes to guessing, I go with my gut instincts in choosing a direction, but with simple logic. I'll explain. About the population, I live in a big city and it's not even the biggest in the state. So, in my city there's like around 3 million people living here. Also the consensus they take every year, I always feel the numbers are inaccurate due to illegal immigrants and citizens being counted multiple times. I was once put on the consensus 3 different times in the same week. Once at my apartment. Once when I was at my parent's home. Once when I was over at a friend's house. So, based on that, I assume the numbers will always be higher. I estimated between  200 and 400 million and took the median 300 as my answer. Hope that made sense. It did in my head, until I reread it, but that's how my brain works.

Truly happy Scorpios are a rare find, I basically used the average population you provided. I figure there's more mysterious and dark Scorpios out there, but even among those there are still some happy scattered in there. Using the 45.5% and 54.4% avg and guessed 10% of  the average are Scorpios. I guessed roughly 4% were happy scorpios.
column107: The news is tricky. I'll be honest. I don't trust the news or social media. I'm not a jump on the bandwagon type. I prefer to look things up and determine for myself if there's any truth or validity to any claims. Even that information can either be minimal but factual, verbose and false, or either can have mixed half-truth and half-false. Also, people who lie will most always try to steer you away from finding out everything or lie in plain sight hoping that will be enough to steer you away.  So, I just went with my gut. In the beginning of the study you mentioned and emphasized there was not trickery going on, so I assumed you would try to steer me away from the bonus. I'm not saying that's what you did. I'm saying, I used that as a position to help guide my instincts. I guessed accordingly.
